{{ pc.standardSection('id="how"') }}
  <h3 id="how-it-works">How It Works</h3>
  <p>
    A release publishes one manifest. Each entry names a module, its change severity and type, a human
    summary, and — when the change is breaking — a reference to the migration that applies it. Tools read
    the manifest; they never parse prose.
  </p>
  {% highlight "json" %}
{
  "manifestVersion": "1",
  "package": "@frontierui/droplist",
  "release": "3.0.0",
  "previous": "2.4.1",
  "entries": [
    {
      "module": "blocks/droplist/AutoComplete.ts",
      "severity": "major",
      "type": "changed",
      "summary": "`filter` prop renamed to `filterStrategy`.",
      "migration": {
        "ref": "migrations/3.0.0/rename-filter-prop.codemod.ts",
        "author": "frontierui",
        "integrity": "sha256-…",
        "rewrites": "consumer call sites of <auto-complete filter>"
      }
    },
    {
      "module": "blocks/droplist/Filter.ts",
      "severity": "patch",
      "type": "fixed",
      "summary": "Diacritic folding now matches `Intl.Collator` sensitivity."
    }
  ]
}
  {% endhighlight %}
  <p>
    The updater derives the package bump from the strictest entry severity (one <code>major</code> entry makes
    the release <code>major</code>), routes the breaking entries through their migrations, and — for a clean
    update — applies them without a human editing a single call site.
  </p>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-changelog-manifest"') }}
  <h3 id="changelog-manifest-protocol">Changelog Manifest Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    Conformance reference for a release's machine-readable change description. A conformant manifest is a dual
    artifact: a <strong>human-readable</strong> projection (Keep a Changelog sections) and a
    <strong>machine schema</strong> (the typed entries above). The protocol standardizes <em>only</em> the
    machine schema and the migration linkage; the human layer is a rendering of the same entries and borrows
    existing vocabulary rather than defining one.
  </p>

  <h4 id="schema-contract">Schema Contract</h4>
  <p>The novel, standardized surface — every conformant manifest entry satisfies this shape:</p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
type Severity = 'major' | 'minor' | 'patch';            // semver, verbatim
type ChangeType =                                        // Keep a Changelog vocabulary
    'added' | 'changed' | 'deprecated' | 'removed' | 'fixed' | 'security';

interface ChangelogEntry {
    // The unit is the module/file, never the whole package.
    module: string;
    severity: Severity;
    type: ChangeType;
    // The human half of the dual format.
    summary: string;
    // Present iff the change is breaking and mechanically applicable.
    migration?: MigrationRef;
}

interface MigrationRef {
    // The codemod that applies this breaking change to consumer source.
    ref: string;
    // Trust metadata — a migration runs on the consumer's code (#101 security step).
    author: string;
    integrity: string;           // content hash of the referenced codemod
    rewrites: string;            // human description of the scope it touches
}

interface ChangelogManifest {
    manifestVersion: string;
    package: string;
    release: string;             // the new version (semver)
    previous: string;           // the version this manifest migrates from
    entries: ChangelogEntry[];
}
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="severity-derivation">Severity Derivation</h4>
  <p>
    The package's release severity is the <strong>strictest entry severity</strong>: any <code>major</code>
    entry makes the release <code>major</code>; otherwise any <code>minor</code> makes it <code>minor</code>;
    else <code>patch</code>. This makes semver a <em>derived</em> fact of the per-module entries, not a
    hand-asserted label — the same strictest-wins reduction the
    <a href="/projects/webvalidation/#protocol-validation">Validation Protocol</a> uses for merged validity.
  </p>

  <h4 id="migration-trust">Migration Trust</h4>
  <p>
    A migration is executable code that rewrites the <em>consumer's</em> source, so it is the manifest's one
    security-sensitive surface. The protocol requires every <code>MigrationRef</code> to carry an
    <code>integrity</code> hash of the referenced codemod and an <code>author</code>, so the
    <a href="/backlog/101-auto-update-pipeline/">auto-update pipeline (#101)</a> can verify a migration before
    running it and refuse one whose hash does not match. The protocol defines the <em>linkage and trust
    fields</em>; how a codemod is authored and how trust is established is the pipeline's security step, not
    this schema's.
  </p>

  <h4 id="consumer-pattern">How Consumers Use the Manifest</h4>
  <we-data-table><table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Consumer</th><th>Reads</th><th>To</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><a href="/backlog/101-auto-update-pipeline/">Auto-update pipeline (#101)</a></td><td>entry severities + migration trust</td><td>classify update risk; verify then apply migrations</td></tr>
      <tr><td><a href="/backlog/094-ai-upgrader-tools/">Upgraders (#094)</a></td><td>migration refs</td><td>run the bundled codemod against consumer call sites</td></tr>
      <tr><td><a href="/backlog/103-incremental-delivery/">Incremental delivery (#103)</a></td><td>changed module list</td><td>ship only the modules whose entries changed</td></tr>
      <tr><td><a href="/backlog/088-module-service-versioning/">MaaS versioning (#088)</a></td><td>derived release severity</td><td>content-address the version bump</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table></we-data-table>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-update-policy"') }}
  <h3 id="update-policy-protocol">Update Policy Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    The <a href="#protocol-changelog-manifest">Changelog Manifest</a> records <em>what changed</em>; the
    <strong>Update Policy</strong> is the committed, portable config that says <em>when a new version is
    adopted and how it is made safe</em> — the Web Everything analogue of <code>renovate.json</code> /
    <code>dependabot.yml</code>. It is the contract behind the
    <a href="/backlog/101-auto-update-pipeline/">auto-update pipeline (#101)</a>: the declared policy is the
    <strong>only lock</strong>, and the orchestration runner that executes it is a swappable
    Plateau/reliability service (<a href="/backlog/497-auto-update-orchestration-runner-plateau-service-execute-the/">the
    deferred build, #497</a>) — the same <em>protocol declares, provider runs</em> split WE already ships in
    <a href="/projects/webguards/#protocol-guard">Guard</a> and
    <a href="/protocols/#protocol-render-strategy">render-strategy</a>.
  </p>

  <h4 id="graded-gate">The gate is one graded axis, not a single mechanic</h4>
  <p>
    No surveyed tool hardcodes one gate; the model is one graded policy keyed to severity + signal, with two
    legitimate poles both shipping in the wild (semantic-release is full-auto; changesets inserts a human
    checkpoint). So the gate is a <strong>configurable dimension</strong> whose safe defaults a project config
    extends — never a baked constant. There are two gates on one axis:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Pre-merge.</strong> Cool-off buffer (<code>minimumReleaseAge</code>) → confidence/severity
      classification read from the changelog-manifest's <a href="#severity-derivation">strictest-wins
      severity</a> → auto-branch + auto-test → <strong>auto-merge patch/minor-green, human-gate major +
      visual-diff</strong>. Breaking entries route through the manifest's migration linkage, run by the
      <a href="/backlog/094-ai-upgrader-tools/">upgrader engine (#094)</a>.</li>
    <li><strong>Post-deploy.</strong> Staged rollout → metric analysis → <strong>auto-rollback on
      regression</strong> (the progressive-delivery metric gate). Its vocabulary is declared in the policy
      now; the runner implements pre-merge first, staged rollout second.</li>
  </ol>

  <h4 id="platform-pretest">Platform-side pre-testing — the WE-only edge</h4>
  <p>
    A Platform-side version can be <strong>pre-tested against its consumers' suites before it is even
    released</strong>, so compatibility is known up front — the
    <a href="/protocols/#protocol-provider-consumer-graph">provider-consumer graph (#092)</a> supplies which
    apps to pre-test. The difference between "hope the bump is safe" and "we already proved it against your
    build." No industry analogue — this is the standard's net-new edge over renovate/dependabot, which can
    only test <em>after</em> a version ships.
  </p>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="protocol-app-shell-compatibility"') }}
  <h3 id="app-shell-compatibility-protocol">App Shell Compatibility Protocol</h3>
  <p>
    Conformance reference for the <strong>flat coexistence manifest</strong> each micro-app authors so a
    minimal-dependency <strong>app shell</strong> can decide, on navigation, whether the next page loads
    <strong>inside the same SPA</strong> (compatible) or needs a <strong>hard refresh</strong> (incompatible) —
    and avoid re-loading code already present. Ruled by
    <a href="/backlog/104-app-shell-compatibility-map/">#104</a>. It is the forward-looking dual of the
    <a href="#protocol-changelog-manifest">Changelog Manifest</a>: where that says <em>what changed</em>, this
    says <em>what I require to run here</em>. The declared chart is the standards lock; the rendered
    <strong>compatibility map</strong> is a separate <a href="/backlog/502-plateau-app-shell-compatibility-map-dashboard-computed-bcd-s/">Plateau
    view (#502)</a> that <em>computes</em> a BCD-style support matrix over the
    <a href="/protocols/#protocol-provider-consumer-graph">#092 provider↔consumer graph</a> — one manifest,
    two consumers (the runtime resolver and the map), the Module Federation 2.0 <code>mf-manifest.json</code>
    one-seam lesson.
  </p>

  <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(5, 150, 105, 0.08); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <h4 style="margin-top: 0; color: #047857; font-size: 1rem;">Declare flat, compute the matrix</h4>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
      A micro-app declares a <strong>minimal requirement manifest</strong>, never a rich support matrix — BCD
      is curated/computed, never declared by implementers, so the declared layer stays flat and the nuance is
      computed by the map. The standardized surface is two parts: a <code>providers</code> block
      (semver ranges, npm-<code>peerDependencies</code> / MF-<code>shared</code> shaped) and the novel
      <code>claims</code> block — OSGi-<code>Require-Capability</code>-style namespaced claims for the
      <strong>DOM dimension</strong> (globals, custom-element tag names, routes) that <em>no</em>
      version-sharing tool (Module Federation, Native Federation, single-spa) models.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h4 id="coexistence-schema-contract">Schema Contract</h4>
  <p>The novel, standardized surface — every conformant coexistence manifest satisfies this shape:</p>
  {% highlight "typescript" %}
type SemverRange = string;   // npm/semver vocabulary, verbatim — e.g. "^2.4.0", ">=18 <20"

interface ProviderRequirement {
    // The shared dependency this app needs from the shell/host (React, a design system, the shell API).
    range: SemverRange;
    // singleton: one instance shared across all active apps -> ranges must INTERSECT (OSGi `uses`).
    // isolatable: each app may load its own version via an import-map scope.
    sharing: 'singleton' | 'isolatable';
    // mandatory: absence/mismatch fails coexistence. optional: degrade, don't fail (peerDependenciesMeta).
    optional?: boolean;       // default false (mandatory)
}

// OSGi-Require-Capability-style namespaced claims for the DOM dimension. A second claimant on the
// same key is a COLLISION (detected separately from a version mismatch). The namespace set is OPEN
// and extensible — globals/tagNames/routes are the ratified floor (#104), not a closed list.
interface CoexistenceClaims {
    globals?: string[];       // window.* keys this app defines/owns
    tagNames?: string[];      // customElements.define() names — collision = two apps define the same tag
    routes?: string[];        // route prefixes this app owns
    [namespace: string]: string[] | undefined;   // future: cssNamespaces, storageKeys, …
}

interface AppShellCompatibilityManifest {
    manifestVersion: string;
    app: string;                              // the micro-app id
    // Required shell/host API range — the asymmetric skew axis (#104): shell NEWER than declared is a
    // forward-compat zone (allow/flag); shell OLDER than required is a hard fail.
    shell: SemverRange;
    providers: Record<string, ProviderRequirement>;   // keyed by provider id
    claims?: CoexistenceClaims;
}
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="coexistence-example">A declared manifest</h4>
  {% highlight "json" %}
{
  "manifestVersion": "1",
  "app": "loan-origination",
  "shell": "^3.0.0",
  "providers": {
    "react": { "range": "^18.2.0", "sharing": "singleton" },
    "@frontierui/droplist": { "range": "^3.0.0", "sharing": "singleton" },
    "chart-lib": { "range": "^5.0.0", "sharing": "isolatable", "optional": true }
  },
  "claims": {
    "globals": ["__LOAN_FLAGS__"],
    "tagNames": ["loan-wizard", "rate-table"],
    "routes": ["/loan", "/underwriting"]
  }
}
  {% endhighlight %}

  <h4 id="coexistence-conformance">Conformance &amp; the strictness knob</h4>
  <p>What the shell (or a build-time validator) checks a manifest set against, before two apps coexist:</p>
  <ul style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    <li><strong>Singleton intersection.</strong> For every <code>singleton</code> provider, the
      <code>range</code>s of all active apps must have a non-empty <em>intersection</em> (the OSGi
      <code>uses</code> constraint) — one shared instance can only satisfy a version all of them accept.
      <code>isolatable</code> providers are exempt (per-app import-map scopes).</li>
    <li><strong>Namespace collision.</strong> Two active apps claiming the same <code>globals</code> /
      <code>tagNames</code> / <code>routes</code> key is a collision — reported <em>separately</em> from a
      version mismatch, because it is a different failure (a custom-element tag can only be defined once).</li>
    <li><strong>Asymmetric shell skew.</strong> Shell <em>newer</em> than the app's declared <code>shell</code>
      range is a forward-compat zone (allow, flag on the map); shell <em>older</em> than required is a hard
      fail — the page needs a hard refresh onto its own shell (Kubernetes version-skew policy).</li>
    <li><strong>Strictness is a warn-by-default policy knob.</strong> A failed check <em>warns</em> by default
      (the app still loads, flagged), and <em>blocks</em> only when the project opts in — mirroring npm
      <code>engine-strict</code> and MF <code>strictVersion</code>, both advisory by default. The default lives
      in the platform config a project extends, not as a baked constant.</li>
  </ul>

  <h4 id="coexistence-authoring-note">Authoring a coexistence manifest</h4>
  <p style="font-size: 0.9rem;">
    Author one manifest per micro-app, committed beside it (the npm-<code>peerDependencies</code> habit). Declare
    only what you <em>require</em> and what you <em>own</em> — never a support matrix. Mark a provider
    <code>singleton</code> when one shared instance is mandatory (a framework runtime, a design-system registry)
    and <code>isolatable</code> when per-app versions are tolerable; mark it <code>optional</code> when its
    absence should degrade rather than fail. List every <code>window.*</code> global, every
    <code>customElements.define()</code> tag, and every owned route under <code>claims</code> so the shell can
    detect collisions before mount. The computed BCD-style matrix, the live dashboard, and the
    <code>status</code>/Baseline surfacing of apps pinned to deprecated providers are the
    <a href="/backlog/502-plateau-app-shell-compatibility-map-dashboard-computed-bcd-s/">Plateau map's (#502)</a>
    job — they read this manifest, they are not authored into it.
  </p>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}

{{ pc.standardSection('id="pattern-deprecation-lifecycle"') }}
  <h3 id="deprecation-lifecycle">Component Deprecation Lifecycle</h3>
  <p>
    Versioning identity answers "what makes two artifacts the same?" (<a href="/backlog/088-module-service-versioning/">#088</a>,
    <a href="/backlog/389/">#389</a>) and the
    <a href="#protocol-changelog-manifest">Changelog Manifest</a> records <em>what changed</em>. The
    <strong>deprecation lifecycle</strong> is the companion <em>pattern</em> that uses both to retire a
    component <strong>without breaking the consumers still on it</strong> — the Web Everything default
    for "this component is going away." It composes the existing standards rather than minting a new
    schema: a deprecation is a <code>changelog-manifest</code> entry, a migration is a
    <a href="/backlog/191-upgrader-version-migration-codemods/">codemod (#191)</a>, and the replacement
    is a new content-addressed version (#088). Modelled on the design-system norm (Shopify Polaris &amp;
    GitHub Primer component lifecycles, the JSDoc <code>@deprecated</code>/<code>@deprecatedSince</code>
    convention, the web platform's own deprecate-then-remove cadence).
  </p>

  <h4 id="lifecycle-stages">The four stages</h4>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Flag</strong> — the component stays fully functional but its <code>changelog-manifest</code>
      entry carries a <code>deprecated</code> marker: a <code>deprecatedSince</code> version, a
      <strong>replacement pointer</strong> (the id/version that supersedes it), and an
      <strong>announced removal milestone</strong>. Tooling surfaces a non-fatal warning at use (console /
      build lint) — <em>flag, don't break</em>, the same stale-while-shown grace the
      <a href="/research/research-freshness-model/">research-freshness model</a> applies to docs.</li>
    <li><strong>New version</strong> — ship the replacement as a distinct content-addressed version
      (#088/#389), never an in-place mutation of the deprecated one. The two coexist; the manifest entry
      links old&nbsp;→&nbsp;new so a consumer (and the upgrader) can resolve the successor.</li>
    <li><strong>Legacy preservation</strong> — across the grace window the old component keeps working via
      one of two support-preserving routes, never a hard cut: a <strong>legacy bundle</strong> (the
      deprecated implementation moved into a separate <code>legacy</code> module so the main surface sheds
      it while call sites keep importing) or a <strong>support-preserving adapter</strong> (a shim that
      maps the old contract onto the new implementation, so one implementation backs both). Codemods (#191)
      supply the <em>automated</em> migration path; the legacy route is the <em>manual/graceful</em> one
      for consumers who have not migrated yet.</li>
    <li><strong>Removal</strong> — only after the announced milestone, and only once the changelog manifest
      shows the migration available, is the legacy route dropped. Removal is itself a
      <code>changelog-manifest</code> entry (a breaking severity), so it flows through the same
      <a href="/backlog/101-auto-update-pipeline/">auto-update</a> classification as any other change.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The invariant: <strong>a consumer is never broken by surprise</strong> — every transition is
    announced in the manifest, a migration exists before removal, and the deprecated component keeps
    working (flagged, not hidden) until the announced removal. <em>Deprecate-don't-delete</em> is the
    component-level analogue of the standard's <em>deprecate-don't-rename</em> identity rule.
  </p>
{{ pc.endStandardSection() }}
